Momentum

An object with mass that is in motion has momentum. It's defined by the equation:

p = m × v

  • p = momentum (kg m/s)
  • m = mass (kg)
  • v = velocity (m/s)

This means a stationary object (v = 0) has no momentum.

Click to explore: Vector Nature

+

Velocity is a vector (it has magnitude and direction). Therefore, momentum is also a vector.

Momentum can be positive or negative depending on its direction of travel. If an object has positive momentum, an object travelling in the opposite direction has negative momentum.

(Please refer to the diagram showing a ball moving in positive and negative directions)

Click to explore: Conservation of Momentum

+

The principle states: In a closed system, the total momentum before an event is equal to the total momentum after the event.

A closed system means there are no external forces acting on the objects (e.g. friction).

Momentum is always conserved in both collisions and explosions.

Click to explore: Collisions & Explosions

+
Collisions:

When objects collide, the total momentum before impact equals the total momentum after. Since momentum is a vector, the momentum of objects moving in opposite directions must be treated as negative.

Explosions:

In an explosion, a single object splits into multiple parts.

  • Initially, the object is stationary, so the total momentum is zero.
  • After the explosion, the parts move in opposite directions.
  • The momentum of one part is equal and opposite to the momentum of the other (e.g., cannon momentum is negative, cannonball momentum is positive).
  • As a result, the total momentum after the explosion is still zero. This is why a cannon recoils.

(Please refer to the diagrams for collisions and explosions to see how momentum is conserved in each case)

Impulse

Impulse is the product of force and the time for which it acts. It is also equal to the change in momentum (Δp).

Impulse = F × Δt = Δp

  • Impulse is measured in (Newton seconds, Ns)
  • F = Force (Newtons, N)
  • Δt = change in time (seconds, s)

Click to explore: Calculating Change in Momentum

+

The change in momentum (Δp) is calculated by subtracting the initial momentum from the final momentum:

Δp = mv - mu

  • mv = final momentum (kg m/s)
  • mu = initial momentum (kg m/s)

Click to explore: Force & Rate of Change

+

By rearranging the impulse-momentum equation, Force can be defined as the rate of change of momentum.

F =
ΔpΔt
